00:17:32.593 --> 00:17:33.240
&gt;&gt;

00:17:33.240 --> 00:17:39.100
&gt;&gt; What so, GINA, or the Genetic Information Nondiscrimination

00:17:39.100 --> 00:17:42.500
Act, was passed in 1995, and what did it do?

00:17:42.500 --> 00:17:47.340
&gt;&gt; GINA was actually signed into law in 2008. It was a very long

00:17:47.340 --> 00:17:52.750
process. So, it, the fight to create GINA first began

00:17:52.750 --> 00:17:57.950
in 1995, you know, a bunch of the bills that eventually became

00:17:57.950 --> 00:18:01.930
GINA started circulating through the government back in 95, and

00:18:01.930 --> 00:18:07.300
probably being talked of even earlier. I'm so sorry, you're,

00:18:07.300 --> 00:18:10.780
&gt;&gt; No, I was going to ask what did what did GINA

00:18:10.780 --> 00:18:16.570
do? What did it say, what was the legal meaning behind it?

00:18:16.570 --> 00:18:22.950
&gt;&gt; Well, GINA's general goal is to prevent discrimination by

00:18:22.950 --> 00:18:29.230
employers with 15 or more employees, or by insurers, based on an individual's

00:18:29.230 --> 00:18:32.389
genetic information or family medical history.

00:18:33.690 --> 00:18:36.260
So they included family medical history in

00:18:36.260 --> 00:18:41.590
part because, y'know, not everyone has had their genome sequenced. But the idea

00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:48.530
is, there are a lot of, this breaks down into a lot of different

00:18:48.530 --> 00:18:50.520
provisions, of course, a lot of different

00:18:50.520 --> 00:18:55.240
individual, granual protections. That the, an insurer

00:18:55.240 --> 00:19:03.180
cannot raise premiums based on the fact that, say, my aunt had breast cancer. I

00:19:03.180 --> 00:19:08.400
may or may not carry one of the BRCA gene variants that would increase my

00:19:08.400 --> 00:19:13.780
likely risk of receiving breast cancer. I cannot be charged under GINA a higher

00:19:13.780 --> 00:19:22.060
premium for that. Likewise, your insurer or your employer cannot require that

00:19:22.060 --> 00:19:26.380
you undergo any type of genetic testing to assess your risk for developing any

00:19:26.380 --> 00:19:33.320
condition. Your, it permits of course in health, a health care provider to

00:19:33.320 --> 00:19:36.530
recommend genetic testing for various purposes. But

00:19:36.530 --> 00:19:39.060
even then, an insurer or an employer

00:19:39.060 --> 00:19:42.290
can only collect the bare minimum of information that

00:19:42.290 --> 00:19:45.630
they need to have for coverage decisions. Basically they

00:19:45.630 --> 00:19:52.010
cannot collect and store additional information regarding your genetic

00:19:52.010 --> 00:19:54.950
Make up predispositions, whatever we're going to call it.

00:19:54.950 --> 00:19:56.510
&gt;&gt; Are there ways around that?

00:19:56.510 --> 00:19:58.680
&gt;&gt; How do you mean?

00:19:58.680 --> 00:20:06.030
&gt;&gt; I'm just wondering you know so legally I can't raise your premium because

00:20:06.030 --> 00:20:07.710
you have the BRCA1 mutation,

00:20:07.710 --> 00:20:07.880
&gt;&gt; Mm hm.

00:20:07.880 --> 00:20:13.421
&gt;&gt; But could I raise your premium for some other reason? I mean, do, are there

00:20:13.421 --> 00:20:20.120
any examples? Workarounds where people do end up discriminating based on these

00:20:23.460 --> 00:20:27.660
based on personal genetic information, anyhow? Or is it just, is

00:20:27.660 --> 00:20:30.860
it not even something people really even try or think about doing?

00:20:30.860 --> 00:20:35.900
&gt;&gt; So far, it really hasn't been an issue. and I think it's. I

00:20:35.900 --> 00:20:39.950
think one of the reasons is because, a lot of the early thought in,

00:20:39.950 --> 00:20:44.490
you know, some of the predecessor builds to GINA was, okay. Sure, you can't

00:20:44.490 --> 00:20:46.100
make someone take a genetic test and

00:20:46.100 --> 00:20:49.180
discriminate against them on that basis, but you

00:20:49.180 --> 00:20:51.960
can take down their family medical history, and discriminate against them

00:20:51.960 --> 00:20:56.320
on that basis. Which, of course, you know, principles of genetic inheritance.

00:20:58.540 --> 00:21:03.360
so that's why that got folded into GINA in the first place. I'm not aware of any

00:21:03.360 --> 00:21:07.110
successful work arounds actually that anyone has tried

00:21:07.110 --> 00:21:12.760
yet. Perhaps that's because it's an iron clad law.

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:13.760
&gt;&gt;

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:13.230
[LAUGH].

00:21:13.230 --> 00:21:15.390
Such a great piece of legislation.

00:21:15.390 --> 00:21:18.930
&gt;&gt; Or more likely the challenges haven't made it into the courts yet.

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:19.930
&gt;&gt;

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:19.540
[LAUGH]

00:21:19.540 --> 00:21:23.120
I could go with either of those. Do

00:21:23.120 --> 00:21:27.500
you feel that concern about genetic discrimination is valid?

00:21:27.500 --> 00:21:33.480
&gt;&gt; Absolutely. I mean,

00:21:33.480 --> 00:21:39.800
you can all to easily imagine an employer, you know, saying,

00:21:40.950 --> 00:21:45.640
you know, let's, let's not say breast cancer, let's say someone who has a

00:21:45.640 --> 00:21:51.030
you know, they've had their genome. they've had their genome coded and they

