show a likelihood, it shows, you know,

00:21:53.600 --> 00:21:55.800
that they will almost certainly develop Huntington's,

00:21:55.800 --> 00:21:56.650
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:21:56.650 --> 00:22:00.175
&gt;&gt; Say, and an employer who wants to make a

00:22:00.175 --> 00:22:02.920
long term investment in an employee if they have access

00:22:02.920 --> 00:22:06.330
to that information, they're allowed to make decisions based on

00:22:06.330 --> 00:22:11.160
it. Might say, you know, we really rather have some

00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:17.100
who'll have a longer working life with us, likewise in insurer. I need insurance

00:22:17.100 --> 00:22:22.220
Make their money based on having the maximum number of

00:22:22.220 --> 00:22:27.310
basically healthy people paying into the insurance pool which then.

00:22:27.310 --> 00:22:27.920
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:22:27.920 --> 00:22:32.670
&gt;&gt; Goes to pay for the less healthy people. it is in the

00:22:32.670 --> 00:22:36.400
insurer's best interest to keep as many people who are going to develop

00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:40.020
serious conditions out of that pool as possible. So yeah, I think

00:22:40.020 --> 00:22:45.210
that's a completely rational concern that people have that led to GINA.

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:47.200
I think it's one of the few occasions when, as you said,

00:22:47.200 --> 00:22:48.580
they got out ahead of the

00:22:48.580 --> 00:22:52.260
possibility of experiencing this type of discrimination.

00:22:52.260 --> 00:22:55.940
&gt;&gt; You know we discussed BRCA1-1 mutations, we talked about the biology

00:22:55.940 --> 00:23:01.850
behind it and we even mention the idea that. And Myriad was

00:23:01.850 --> 00:23:07.520
a company that patented the human gene sequences, the mutations,

00:23:07.520 --> 00:23:12.870
that cause, that are the BRCA1-2 mutation. And these patents have allowed

00:23:12.870 --> 00:23:18.210
them to develop a diagnostic acid that no one else can touch that

00:23:18.210 --> 00:23:22.710
are the three dominant BRCA1-2 mutations. And they

00:23:22.710 --> 00:23:27.450
have fought vociferously in the courts to

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:28.880
keep those patents.

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:30.480
&gt;&gt; It was a long and bloody battle.

00:23:30.480 --> 00:23:34.930
&gt;&gt; What what is the current state of gene patenting in the United States?

00:23:34.930 --> 00:23:40.780
&gt;&gt; So the current state of gene patenting, thanks to the decision on

00:23:40.780 --> 00:23:46.799
June 2013, I think it was June 13th, 2013. On the myriad case,

00:23:46.799 --> 00:23:53.770
is that human genetic code is not patentable.

00:23:53.770 --> 00:23:59.650
However, code that is synthesized from, like

00:23:59.650 --> 00:24:06.100
if you, I cannot say, I patent that mutation you have, because I discovered it!

00:24:06.100 --> 00:24:11.220
However, if you synthesize that DNA, a thing that's called CDNA

00:24:11.220 --> 00:24:11.395
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:24:11.395 --> 00:24:18.150
&gt;&gt; That is patentable, because that is a product of human innovation.

00:24:19.190 --> 00:24:25.120
So a lot of the debate over the myriad case and the patenting of genes. Has

00:24:25.120 --> 00:24:32.080
really been about the purpose of patents in the United States. And you

00:24:32.080 --> 00:24:34.010
know this whole history of intellectual property

00:24:34.010 --> 00:24:36.430
protection in the United States. Which is super

00:24:36.430 --> 00:24:40.409
fun stuff that probably doesn't need to be done in depth in a Genetics Course.

00:24:42.520 --> 00:24:46.190
but the purpose of patent code is to

00:24:46.190 --> 00:24:50.180
protect the fruits of, human innovation. Either if you

00:24:50.180 --> 00:24:54.300
have worked on something. And you have created something.

00:24:54.300 --> 00:24:56.940
You are entitled to control it and profit off

00:24:56.940 --> 00:24:59.620
of that. For, you know, protected period of

00:24:59.620 --> 00:25:02.150
time. Which has changed of course, throughout patent protection

00:25:02.150 --> 00:25:05.080
history. Which you're entitled to exclusively profit off of

00:25:05.080 --> 00:25:07.680
that for a period of time as a reward

00:25:07.680 --> 00:25:09.620
for your labor in bringing this new

00:25:09.620 --> 00:25:13.670
thing into the world. So patenting of natural

00:25:13.670 --> 00:25:18.460
materials has actually been, there's a pretty

00:25:18.460 --> 00:25:22.610
extensive case law that this was not something

00:25:22.610 --> 00:25:27.860
that you could do. Because you can't just, you know, discover a mold, scoop it

00:25:27.860 --> 00:25:33.230
out and say, I patent this, I get to use this mold alone. A lot

00:25:33.230 --> 00:25:39.040
of people were arguing that genes, the discovery of genetic

00:25:39.040 --> 00:25:44.770
mutation, took so much effort and took so much ingenuity to isolate. And

00:25:44.770 --> 00:25:49.010
to interpret this information, that that made it patentable.

00:25:50.370 --> 00:25:55.670
And, there actually you know, Myriads patents were not the first to be issued.

00:25:55.670 --> 00:25:57.210
&gt;&gt; Mhmm.

00:25:57.210 --> 00:25:58.690
&gt;&gt; Myriad was really just

00:25:58.690 --> 00:26:01.518
the worst behaved patenter

00:26:01.518 --> 00:26:02.858
[LAUGH]

00:26:02.858 --> 00:26:05.220
a of human genetic information.

00:26:05.220 --> 00:26:06.580
&gt;&gt; They didn't make any friends.

00:26:06.580 --> 00:26:07.620
&gt;&gt; Exactly.

00:26:07.620 --> 00:26:09.310
&gt;&gt; Even since the Supreme Court decision, it

00:26:09.310 --> 00:26:11.580
seems that they're still going after people. I know

00:26:11.580 --> 00:26:13.600
that there are companies that, you know, were

00:26:13.600 --> 00:26:15.560
trying to run with the Supreme Court decision and.

00:26:15.560 --> 00:26:16.101
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:26:16.101 --> 00:26:17.800
&gt;&gt; Myriad is still suing them.

00:26:17.800 --> 00:26:22.400
&gt;&gt; Yes. Yeah, there, there's plenty of clean-up work left to be done.

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:23.400
&gt;&gt;

00:26:22.400 --> 00:26:22.848
[LAUGH]

00:26:22.848 --> 00:26:24.390
&gt;&gt; But yeah, over the course of this

00:26:24.390 --> 00:26:28.330
litigation, people were arguing. Instead of invalidating patents

00:26:28.330 --> 00:26:30.160
like this then having this sort of compulsory

00:26:30.160 --> 00:26:34.670
licensing system was another idea that's you know, common

00:26:34.670 --> 00:26:38.990
to further scientific innovation by licensing your patent.

00:26:38.990 --> 00:26:43.550
Licensing your discovery. And the whole problem with myriad's

00:26:43.550 --> 00:26:45.050
holding of all these patents that led to

00:26:45.050 --> 00:26:48.660
all these lawsuits is they didn't grant any licenses.

00:26:48.660 --> 00:26:55.280
Which was putting a choke hold on research. And of course an individuals ability

00:26:55.280 --> 00:26:57.550
to access a diagnostic test to determine

00:26:57.550 --> 00:26:59.450
whether or not they had these mutations.

00:26:59.450 --> 00:27:02.670
&gt;&gt; Now, what about other genes, so, I mean, obviously

00:27:02.670 --> 00:27:05.380
we can't patent human genes, can we patent cat genes,

00:27:05.380 --> 00:27:08.870
can we patent tree genes, can we patent bacteria genes?

00:27:08.870 --> 00:27:14.810
Unless they are synthesized, and therefore a product of human innovation,

00:27:14.810 --> 00:27:15.610
they're not patentable.

00:27:15.610 --> 00:27:17.920
&gt;&gt; Now what I find fascinating, and I don't even

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:19.600
know if you're aware of this or not, but CDNA.

00:27:19.600 --> 00:27:20.060
&gt;&gt; Mm-hm.

00:27:20.060 --> 00:27:22.820
&gt;&gt; And our students don't know about this yet, we haven't talked about it in

00:27:22.820 --> 00:27:28.770
the course, but CDNA is a type of DNA Created when take an MRNA, which is

00:27:28.770 --> 00:27:33.100
when we have a gene in our cell, and it's turned on, it's transcribed into an

00:27:33.100 --> 00:27:41.100
MRNA. We have enzymes that can we can, in a lab, add to that mix and

00:27:41.100 --> 00:27:45.190
turn that MRNA back into DNA. And the interesting thing

00:27:45.190 --> 00:27:48.900
about MRNA is it's spliced together. It originally starts out really

00:27:48.900 --> 00:27:51.110
long, but we cut a lot of pieces of the MRNA

00:27:51.110 --> 00:27:53.310
out, and the resulting MRNA is really short, and it just

00:27:53.310 --> 00:27:56.570
has the genetic information that gets turned into the protein.

00:27:56.570 --> 00:27:59.680
So when you turn an MRNA back into CDNA, you only

00:27:59.680 --> 00:28:02.340
get the relevant coding information that was used, but a gene

00:28:02.340 --> 00:28:06.500
is actually much bigger. A gene itself has tons of information,

00:28:06.500 --> 00:28:09.010
called entrons, that don't end up in the final

00:28:09.010 --> 00:28:12.300
product. But there are genes that don't have entrons, that

00:28:12.300 --> 00:28:16.100
are just entron-less. So the MRNA is pretty much

00:28:16.100 --> 00:28:19.130
the same length as the gene itself. And I'm really

00:28:19.130 --> 00:28:20.810
curious to know what the supreme court thinks of

00:28:20.810 --> 00:28:24.255
that, because technically the information within a CDNA of an

00:28:24.255 --> 00:28:27.440
entron-less gene is the exact same as the gene

00:28:27.440 --> 00:28:31.510
itself. So I just wonder how you know if it

00:28:31.510 --> 00:28:36.800
really is about the nature of the, of the molecule, or if it has to do

00:28:36.800 --> 00:28:39.610
more with the information in the molecule. Like

00:28:39.610 --> 00:28:41.470
is it, is it the idea that it's synthesized?

00:28:41.470 --> 00:28:41.950
&gt;&gt; Hm-mm.

00:28:41.950 --> 00:28:43.490
&gt;&gt; Or is it the idea that the

00:28:43.490 --> 00:28:46.830
particular order of the information is not natural?

00:28:46.830 --> 00:28:51.730
&gt;&gt; That is a really, I mean I think that will be an interesting question when

00:28:51.730 --> 00:28:57.140
it inevitably turns up in court. Because the idea at this point is

00:28:57.140 --> 00:29:02.480
that you can patent something that is synthesized. I don't know what to tell you

00:29:02.480 --> 00:29:04.500
that if the product that you synthesized

00:29:04.500 --> 00:29:10.300
is informationally completely identical to the natural product.

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:17.940
I mean, the. Although, then, the CDNA that you're working on

00:29:17.940 --> 00:29:22.270
would still be something that you've produced in the lab. The CDNA.

00:29:22.270 --> 00:29:22.890
&gt;&gt; Absolutely.

00:29:22.890 --> 00:29:25.120
&gt;&gt; That is, you know, being circulated to other labs to

00:29:25.120 --> 00:29:29.830
do their research on. That is a lab product. As opposed

00:29:29.830 --> 00:29:33.310
to, you know, I took a sample from Matt, and I

00:29:33.310 --> 00:29:37.770
worked on that because it's informationally identical to the cDNA. So.

00:29:37.770 --> 00:29:39.640
&gt;&gt; Hmm. I'll

00:29:39.640 --> 00:29:40.700
be interested, yeah, I mean.

00:29:40.700 --> 00:29:43.080
&gt;&gt; I'll be interested to see how that, how that shakes out.

00:29:43.080 --> 00:29:43.170
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:29:43.170 --> 00:29:45.950
&gt;&gt; But at this time, the distinction really is

00:29:45.950 --> 00:29:49.580
in the Have you synthesized it? Have you altered

00:29:49.580 --> 00:29:52.500
this from its natural state? And it's not really

00:29:52.500 --> 00:29:54.300
about information altering, although it's

00:29:54.300 --> 00:29:56.620
usually about purifying and distilling.

